{"id":14881411,"mediaExerciseId":"93f7be5b-a17e-4e9f-86bf-9e98c868e9c6","exerciseName":"12","chapterName":"13","chapterTitle":"Return, Risk, and The Security Market Line","groupId":612376,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":453,"solutions":[{"id":5998267,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to determine a stock's beta. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":28,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/5d7a0c1ba46ddc94cfde0099d8b48b7e/lateximg_large.png","width":762},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/5d7a0c1ba46ddc94cfde0099d8b48b7e/lateximg.png","width":382}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"\nThe **capital asset pricing model (CAPM)** is an equation that shows how systematic risk and expected returns are related. The CAPM informs us that the expected return is influenced by the time value of money, theÂ risk premium, and the stock's beta compared to an average value.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":143,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/b65998f78dc9bf13718fbb6ccc9951a4/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/b65998f78dc9bf13718fbb6ccc9951a4/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's first identify the given amounts in the problem: \n\n\n| | Amount$\\hspace{5pt}$| \n|:--|--:| \n|Beta of one stock |1.17|\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":61,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/fdaa40cf93511b25ac20ac44a3815f99/lateximg_large.png","width":776},"regular":{"height":32,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/fdaa40cf93511b25ac20ac44a3815f99/lateximg.png","width":390}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's start by determining the value of the stocks required in the following steps.\n\nOne of the stocks is risk-free, implying an investment made with no risk premium. A zero-beta investment with the same expected return as the **risk-free rate has no risk premium**.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":179,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/16551e4b81b94da71d88cb4aa20639d0/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/16551e4b81b94da71d88cb4aa20639d0/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"We also noticed that the problem said that the investment as a whole is equally as volatile as the market, meaning that the stock's beta is the same as the market's. Because the **market's beta is one**, we conclude the investment's beta is one as well.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":135,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/b51a8fe296464e6eccad99017e7ebabe/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":69,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/b51a8fe296464e6eccad99017e7ebabe/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"We can now calculate the value of the missing stock. We'll use the equation below to help us understand how to compute the beta. We'll use X as the beta for which we'll do our calculations. Here's how it works:\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Total portfolio }&={(}\\dfrac{\\text{1}}{\\text{3}}{\\text{ $\\times$ 1.17) +}}{(}\\dfrac{\\text{1}}{\\text{3}}{\\text{ $\\times$ 0)+ }}{(}\\dfrac{\\text{1}}{\\text{3}}{\\text{ $\\times$ X)}}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nAs you have noticed, we multiplied each value by 1/3, and this is because there are three stocks in this portfolio. We are trying to find the beta of the 3rd stock. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":323,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/45e702f7a4fd20c6388cbcf4e38eaa3a/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":164,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/45e702f7a4fd20c6388cbcf4e38eaa3a/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"Now, let us multiply each value in the equation we have determined in the previous step. This is computed as follows: \n\n \n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{1 }&={\\text{0.39 +}}{}{\\text{0 + }}\\dfrac{\\text{X}}{\\text{3}}{\\text{}}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":163,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/e5c623462867effb070009f39f235d8f/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":82,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/e5c623462867effb070009f39f235d8f/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7},{"columns":[{"text":"Then, we must rearrange the formula by shifting the 0.39 to one side. This is computed as follows: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{1 }&={\\text{0.39 +}}\\dfrac{\\text{X}}{\\text{3}}{\\text{}}\\\\\n\\text{1 - 0.39 }&=\\dfrac{\\text{X}}{\\text{3}}{\\text{}}\\\\\n\\text{0.61 }&=\\dfrac{\\text{X}}{\\text{3}}{\\text{}}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":309,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/af822c114374a0e489e056aa452c4415/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":156,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/af822c114374a0e489e056aa452c4415/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":8},{"columns":[{"text":"Then, we must rearrange the formula again by shifting the X to one side. This is computed as follows: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\n\\text{X }&={\\text{0.61 $\\times$3}}\\\\\n&={\\textbf{1.83}}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":9},{"columns":[{"text":"**To conclude, the beta value of the third stock in the portfolio is 1.83.**\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":30,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/6019ef8e943aa1af2c33c1aee9296ce6/lateximg_large.png","width":979},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/c4fa274e69a2d61d257620fe82e7e1c4/6019ef8e943aa1af2c33c1aee9296ce6/lateximg.png","width":491}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":10}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"44a66742-3940-490b-b10d-e4f6aa3a07c9","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":10}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":